            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Philistidas, son of Euxenos, the ropemaker</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>An unusual example of an archaic funerary inscription with indication of the deceased's profession: the restoration of initial Κ and  interpretation of καλωποιός as 'rope-maker' is due to Orsi. The stone was presumed  lost  by Dubois (and speculatively attributed to Palermo Museum in LSAG(2), but seems always to have been in the Syracuse museum since its deposit in 1900.<!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!-- Jeffery Archive: J.WC 54 p.01. --></p>
            </div>
